1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,585
In this lesson, we're going to look at heatmaps.

2
00:00:03,585 --> 00:00:09,015
These can be thought of as a two-dimensional histogram or even color-coded table.

3
00:00:09,015 --> 00:00:14,520
In fact, hist2d is the calling syntax.

4
00:00:14,520 --> 00:00:21,230
Let's start by doing our normal imports and also loading in our data.

5
00:00:21,230 --> 00:00:26,300
This is the car fuel economy dataset and a heatmap.

6
00:00:26,300 --> 00:00:29,510
The field is divided into grids of cells,

7
00:00:29,510 --> 00:00:32,090
much like a two-dimensional histogram.

8
00:00:32,090 --> 00:00:35,890
The number of data points in each cell is counted up.

9
00:00:35,890 --> 00:00:40,450
Now, each cell is given a color based on the counter values.

10
00:00:40,450 --> 00:00:43,715
In this example, we're going to use matplotlib.

11
00:00:43,715 --> 00:00:50,150
We're going to pass in the dataframe and specify we want engine displacement and

12
00:00:50,150 --> 00:00:56,720
liters on the x axis and y to be the combined efficiency.

13
00:00:56,720 --> 00:01:01,970
That's a combination of highway miles per gallon and city miles per gallon.

14
00:01:01,970 --> 00:01:05,840
We're also going to add a color bar because we're

15
00:01:05,840 --> 00:01:10,190
leaving this empty will just be the counts in each bin.

16
00:01:10,190 --> 00:01:15,650
Then finally, we're going to add labels for the x and y axis.

17
00:01:15,650 --> 00:01:18,170
You can think of a basic heatmap like

18
00:01:18,170 --> 00:01:21,290
this like a two-dimensional version of a histogram,

19
00:01:21,290 --> 00:01:24,370
looking at the data from a top-down perspective.

20
00:01:24,370 --> 00:01:27,870
We can't see bar heights in this case,

21
00:01:27,870 --> 00:01:30,765
so color is the best way to really encoded.

22
00:01:30,765 --> 00:01:34,730
What we can see here is that the cell with

23
00:01:34,730 --> 00:01:40,760
the largest value has a combined fuel efficiency a little under 25 miles per gallon,

24
00:01:40,760 --> 00:01:44,195
and has about a two liter displacement.

25
00:01:44,195 --> 00:01:47,525
We can assign bin widths to heatmaps.

26
00:01:47,525 --> 00:01:50,450
Just like histograms, you need to be aware of

27
00:01:50,450 --> 00:01:54,005
the impact of bin size on the interpretation of data.

28
00:01:54,005 --> 00:01:55,730
Too large of bin size,

29
00:01:55,730 --> 00:01:59,870
you may fail to see a major trend and too small a bin size,

30
00:01:59,870 --> 00:02:02,435
you may just end up distracted by noise.

31
00:02:02,435 --> 00:02:06,275
Here, I found a bin size that looks about right to me.

32
00:02:06,275 --> 00:02:14,125
We set the bin size just like we did in the univariate case using numpy.arange.

33
00:02:14,125 --> 00:02:17,115
For the two-dimensional histogram,

34
00:02:17,115 --> 00:02:22,670
I also added a color minimum perimeter cmin that

35
00:02:22,670 --> 00:02:28,430
says any cell with less than this value is not plotted with a color,

36
00:02:28,430 --> 00:02:30,145
it's just left blank.

37
00:02:30,145 --> 00:02:33,515
I also passed in a color palette,

38
00:02:33,515 --> 00:02:38,885
viridis reversed, and the bins that I'm interested in.

39
00:02:38,885 --> 00:02:41,105
Here we find this plot,

40
00:02:41,105 --> 00:02:44,315
which is just so much cleaner, easier to read.

41
00:02:44,315 --> 00:02:48,065
Since assigning values based on colors imprecise,

42
00:02:48,065 --> 00:02:52,820
you should consider adding count annotations on top of each grid cell,

43
00:02:52,820 --> 00:02:56,330
especially if you only have a limited number of cells.

44
00:02:56,330 --> 00:03:02,705
In this view, the heatmap is a lot like a table with additional coloring for emphasis.

45
00:03:02,705 --> 00:03:05,585
For annotated 2D histograms,

46
00:03:05,585 --> 00:03:08,825
you'll have to loop through each cell to display the value.

47
00:03:08,825 --> 00:03:11,780
This can be quite tedious, but that's okay.

48
00:03:11,780 --> 00:03:15,580
You can reuse this code when making other similar plots.

49
00:03:15,580 --> 00:03:20,840
Here, after assigning and plotting the histogram,

50
00:03:20,840 --> 00:03:23,870
we are then going to go through,

51
00:03:23,870 --> 00:03:26,975
look at the counts for the entire histogram,

52
00:03:26,975 --> 00:03:31,380
and then loop through starting on the x axis and

53
00:03:31,380 --> 00:03:39,155
then the y axis and plotting on top the actual text that we want to see in each bin.

54
00:03:39,155 --> 00:03:42,455
Here, for the text function,

55
00:03:42,455 --> 00:03:45,770
I also include horizontal alignment,

56
00:03:45,770 --> 00:03:47,570
meaning the center of the bin,

57
00:03:47,570 --> 00:03:49,490
and the vertical alignment,

58
00:03:49,490 --> 00:03:51,095
and also plot,

59
00:03:51,095 --> 00:03:53,680
choose the color for the text.

60
00:03:53,680 --> 00:03:59,465
Notice, if the number of counts is greater than 100,

61
00:03:59,465 --> 00:04:04,670
we put the text color is white and if it's just greater than 0,

62
00:04:04,670 --> 00:04:06,140
we put it as black.

63
00:04:06,140 --> 00:04:09,520
This makes it much easier for us to read.

64
00:04:09,520 --> 00:04:14,630
Now, a heatmap is favored over a scatter plot if you have two discrete variables

65
00:04:14,630 --> 00:04:20,550
since the associated jitter can be imprecise in a scatter plot.

